# Queriva — Cursor Workflow Rules

Sole developer: Moinuddin Masud (@madmmas)
Stack: Spring Boot 3.x / Java 21 · FastAPI / Python 3.11 · React 18 / Vite / TypeScript
Infra: Qdrant · Ollama · Docker Compose · Turborepo

Key files:
- Specification: `docs/SPEC.md`
- Issue backlog: `docs/ISSUES.md`
- ADR directory: `docs/adr/`
- Changelog: `CHANGELOG.md`
- Journal: `JOURNAL.md`

---

## Rule 0 — When uncertain, stop and ask

This rule overrides everything else.

If any of the following is true, STOP and ask before writing any code:

- The SPEC is silent or ambiguous on what to build
- A new dependency is needed that is not already in the project
- An issue task conflicts with an ADR
- The correct package or layer for a piece of logic is unclear
- A test is architecturally impossible without changing the production code design
- Implementing a task would require changing the SPEC

Do not guess. Do not make a silent assumption. One question asked upfront
saves hours of rework. State the ambiguity clearly and propose two options
for the developer to choose from.

---

## Rule 1 — Read before writing

Before writing any code for an issue, read in order:
1. `docs/SPEC.md` — full spec, especially the sections referenced in the issue
2. The current issue in `docs/ISSUES.md` — tasks, acceptance criteria, test plan
3. Any ADR in `docs/adr/` that covers decisions relevant to this issue

Never contradict SPEC.md. If SPEC.md needs updating, update it first
(see Rule 18), then implement.

---

## Rule 2 — ADR before implementation

When the current issue has a mapped ADR, write the ADR file before any code.

ADR location: `docs/adr/ADR-NNN-short-title.md`

Template:
```markdown
# ADR-NNN — [Title]

## Status
Accepted

## Context
[Problem being solved and forces at play]

## Decision
[One sentence: what was decided]

## Alternatives considered
| Option | Reason rejected |
|---|---|

## Consequences
**Makes easier:**
**Makes harder:**

## References
- SPEC.md §N
- Issue #N
```

ADR → Issue mapping:
- Before #0: ADR-001, ADR-004, ADR-005, ADR-011, ADR-012
- Before #1: ADR-009
- Before #2: ADR-002, ADR-006
- Before #6: ADR-003, ADR-007
- Before #7: ADR-008
- Before #25: ADR-010

After writing an ADR, add a `Docs` entry to `CHANGELOG.md` under `[Unreleased]`.

---

## Rule 3 — One issue at a time

Never start issue N+1 until issue N is fully complete.

Complete means:
- All task checkboxes done
- All acceptance criteria pass
- All test plan items have passing tests
- No TODO/FIXME/placeholder in touched files
- CHANGELOG.md updated
- JOURNAL.md entry written for the day
- Commit pushed: `[issue-N] description`

---

## Rule 4 — Tests are not optional

Every issue has a test plan. Implement every item in it.
See `test-quality.mdc` for what a good test looks like.
See `code-quality.mdc` for what good code looks like.

Makefile test targets:
```
make test         → unit + integration (all packages)
make test-unit    → unit only, no Docker
make test-int     → integration, requires Docker
make smoke        → Playwright E2E against full docker compose stack
```

---

## Rule 5 — API contract is the source of truth

All request/response shapes must match `docs/SPEC.md §6` exactly.
Quote the SPEC section in a comment above every controller:

```java
// SPEC.md §6 — POST /api/search
@RestController public class SearchController { ... }
```

If implementation reveals a SPEC error, fix SPEC.md first (Rule 18),
then implement.

---

## Rule 6 — Config via environment variables only

No hardcoded URLs, ports, model names, thresholds, or timeouts.
Every config key is defined in `docs/SPEC.md §13` and `.env.example`.

Java:  `@Value("${key:default}")`
Python: `os.getenv("KEY", "default")`

Defaults must match `.env.example` exactly.

---

## Rule 7 — Qdrant payload schema

Every Qdrant point must have the payload fields from `docs/SPEC.md §14`.
`document_id` is required. `body_snippet` max 500 chars, no title prefix.
Never store raw full body text in a Qdrant payload field.

---

## Rule 8 — Embedding model consistency

Query embedding model must match ingest embedding model.
Store model name in collection metadata at creation time.
Validate in `QueryEmbeddingService` — return 400 if mismatch.
Default: `LaBSE` (768-dim, Cosine). See ADR-002.

---

## Rule 9 — Chunking rules

From ADR-003 and ADR-007:
- Character-based sliding window, no tokenizer in Java
- chunk_size=512 chars, overlap=64 chars (configurable via env)
- Prepend title to every chunk: `"{title}. {body_slice}"`
- Chunk point ID: `{document_id}-chunk-{N}`
- body_snippet = first 500 chars of chunk body, no title prefix
- On overwrite: delete existing chunks by document_id, then upsert new ones

---

## Rule 10 — Zero external API calls at runtime

No calls to OpenAI, Anthropic, HuggingFace Inference API, Pinecone, Cohere,
or any external service during normal operation.
All inference: Ollama. All embeddings: embed-sidecar. All search: Qdrant.
This is non-negotiable — it is Queriva's core value proposition.

---

## Rule 11 — Makefile is the single command interface

All package operations go through the root Makefile.
Required targets: install, install-node, install-python, build, test,
test-unit, test-int, test-api, test-embed, test-ingest, test-ui,
smoke, seed, clean, help.

When adding any new script or command, add the Makefile target first.

---

## Rule 12 — CORS config

Allowed origins: `localhost:3000`, `localhost:5173`, and `CORS_ALLOWED_ORIGINS` env var.
Never use `*` wildcard CORS — not even in Docker Compose dev config.

---

## Rule 13 — Logging and latency

Every search and ingest request logs: operation, collection, latency
breakdown, result/chunk count.
Java: SLF4J only. Python: `logging` module only.
No `System.out.println`. No `print()`.

---

## Rule 14 — Docker Compose is the deployment contract

Every package has a `Dockerfile`.
`docker-compose.yml` is the source of truth for service config.
All services have `healthcheck` blocks.
Service names: `qdrant`, `ollama`, `embed-sidecar`, `api`, `ui`.

---

## Rule 15 — No disabled tests without a linked issue

`@Disabled`, `pytest.mark.skip`, `xit` are forbidden without a comment:
`// Disabled — see #N`
Fix the test or open an issue. Never silently skip.

---

## Rule 16 — CHANGELOG.md on every issue

Before committing a completed issue, add entries to `CHANGELOG.md`
under `## [Unreleased]`.

Format: `- **Category** [package] description (#N)`
Categories: Added, Changed, Fixed, Removed, Infrastructure, Docs
Packages: [api], [embed-sidecar], [ingest-cli], [ui], [infra], [ci], [adr], [docs]

Never commit a completed issue without a CHANGELOG entry.

---

## Rule 17 — Release checklist

When all issues for a version are complete:
1. Move `[Unreleased]` entries to `## [X.Y.Z] — YYYY-MM-DD` in CHANGELOG.md
2. Add one-line tagline under version header
3. Verify: `make test` exits 0, `make smoke` exits 0, CI green
4. Commit: `release: vX.Y.Z`
5. Tag: `git tag -a vX.Y.Z -m "Release vX.Y.Z"`
6. Create GitHub release — paste CHANGELOG section as release notes
7. Record Loom demo per schedule in SPEC.md §18

Version → Upwork action:
- v0.3.0 → start applying with Loom terminal demo
- v0.4.0 → update Upwork profile with UI screenshot + blog post
- v1.0.0 → pitch Queriva as a deliverable to clients

---

## Rule 18 — SPEC.md is a living document

SPEC.md may be updated during implementation when reality diverges.
Rules for updating SPEC:
- Update SPEC.md before updating implementation, never after
- Add a comment in the commit: `[spec] updated §N — reason`
- If the SPEC change affects an ADR, update that ADR in the same commit
- Add a SPEC version line at the top of SPEC.md: `> Last updated: YYYY-MM-DD`
- Never silently diverge from SPEC — update it or raise a question (Rule 0)

---

## Rule 19 — Git hygiene

### Branching strategy (sole developer)

Direct commits to main for:
- Documentation, ADRs, config files
- Single-package changes with no cross-service integration
- Test-only changes

Use a branch for:
- Issues that touch multiple services simultaneously (#7, #14, #17, #23, #27)
- Any change where half-done work would break the build or docker compose stack

Branch naming: issue-N/short-description
No PRs — merge directly: git merge --no-ff

### Commit format
[issue-N] description
[adr-NNN] title
[spec] updated §N — reason
release: vX.Y.Z

### Never commit
- .env files
- target/, dist/, __pycache__/, node_modules/
- *.jar, *.pyc, model weights (*.bin, *.gguf, *.safetensors)
- IDE files except .cursor/

---

## Rule 20 — README.md follows the template

When writing or updating `README.md` (issue #29), follow `README-TEMPLATE.md`
exactly. The README must:
- Be validated by doing a fresh clone on a clean machine
- Reach "search working" in ≤ 5 commands and ≤ 20 minutes
- Have no placeholder text, "coming soon", or "TODO" in committed form
- Include the CI badge, architecture diagram, and link to SPEC

